metadata.name: The beauty of imperfection #14
metadata.description:
Drawing shapes repeatedly, spinning and rotating. I use basic shapes like square, rectangle, and triangle to create this art. Regular shapes are perfect but it's a little bit boring, so I make them imperfect, just like "hand drawing". I also tried to make this generative art great for physical print, so that I can hang it on the wall. Here we go.

5 background colors:
Black, White, Blue, Green, and Red

Press “space” to play animation.
Press “s” to save.

Made with p5js.
Created by Costa C. | OneRocket.nft

metadata.name: Ordinary Places #27
metadata.description:
“Ordinary Places” is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher’s “Water Tower” photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha’s “26 Gasoline Stations” photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather’s farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Migration #21
metadata.description:
"Migration" is a generative work with which I want to ease my worries about the irresponsibility of people towards the planet they live on.
If we migrate, I hope it will be for the purpose of exploring new areas and not because we have destroyed the planet we live on and are now forced to flee.

Created with 100% p5.js code and math.

Hi-res. options:

- press 'i' to save .png with resolution = 1000px x 1000px
- press 't' to save .png with resolution = 2000px x 2000px
- press 's' to save .png with resolution = 6000px x 6000px


@Mutart, July, 2022.

metadata.name: Retrospect #63
metadata.description:
If it were possible, would you do things differently in retrospect?

A continuation of the exploration of the tension between freedom of choice and fate. Are the decisions we make imperfect, yet beautiful, or are they perfect, yet not beautiful?

meezwhite × July 19, 2022


To give the final result a slight retro feel, it is purposefully fuzzified and a filter layer of carefully picked 70s colors is mixed in. 

Click, tap or press [X] to invert colors.

metadata.name: Loomnatic #17
metadata.description:
"Loomnatic" is a lunatic loom who loves to weave. It sometimes generates fabrics you can see in real life. However, most of the time, its outputs would look extraordinary.

How the loom "weaves" a fabric:
- Create a vector field for the warp threads with the improved Perlin noise developed by Ken Perlin.
- Derive a new vector field from the old one for the weft threads by rotating its angles.
- Calculate the curve vertices with an algorithm developed by Bruno Jobard and Wilfrid Lefer that creates evenly-spaced streamlines of arbitrary density.
- Interpolate each set of curve vertices to form a Catmull-Rom spline and then convert it to a thread polygon with varying thread weights.
- Calculate the intersection polygons of all pairs of interweaving threads with math and geometry.
- Use the intersection polygons to create the textile effect during the drawing stage.

Every token can output in 13 different aspect ratios:
1x1, 3x1, 1x3, 3x2, 2x3, 4x3, 3x4, 5x4, 4x5, 16x9, 9x16, 16x10, 10x16

And downloadable in 4 different resolutions:
1. 1000px
2. 2000px
3. 4000px
4. 8000px

Click on the image in live view to unlock all these possibilities.

Created with Vanilla JavaScript.

metadata.name: Quantum Folly #236
metadata.description:
This piece explores humanity's vanity and obsession with controlling natural forces. In the end we are beholden to the whims of the universe and its rules. What we think is artificial is but nature's inclination.

As an atom gazes at the world it can see the arrogant hand of mankind imposing its will. We are nature's inane creation built from imperceptible, discrete particles.

Enjoy watching the structures form. Due to the nature of the system it may take some time to complete. Once it's fully rendered you can download a full resolution image of 3508 x 4961 px by ***double clicking/tapping***. At this size the piece is printable at A3 size at 300 dpi. If you're interested in acquiring a signed print please contact @KRANKARTA.

Features include: palette, orientation, architecture, particle rules, boundary seepage and colour displacement.

Created on Chrome desktop 103.0 on 2022-07-21 in javascript and GLSL. Results on other browsers/devices may vary.

metadata.name: Causality #10
metadata.description:
A response to the phenomenon of cause and effect. 

We think ourselves to be smart creatures for we have the ability to think, make decisions and communicate. And yet, we also often have to face the consequences of our past actions as we might have been short sighted in our purview in the past, maybe just as we might be even now. And we shall no not unless the future arrives. And to make matters a tiny bit more complex, my decisions might affect your reality and your decision may affect mine. 

We all understand causality, just like we understand Newton's third law of motion. The problem isn't in our understanding but in the limits we try to impose on it. For example, a person who doesn't wish to be short sighted will think of the future. But what does that mean? How exactly far out into the future should or even could a person think of? For you can always add another day to that same number hence making it quite the wicked problem. 

Causality ehh! A generative artwork made in cables.gl.

Press '1,2,3,4,5' to increase the resolution
Press 's' in LIVE mode to save a screenshot

Jaalibandar 2022

metadata.name: ____ - Iteration 2 #426
metadata.description:
This project is part of a larger experiment that explores and celebrates the process of making generative art by progressively releasing iterations, working towards a final release on my main account (tz1RkYY3jr1ocuPdQqrRefr5FqoawKQsmBmD). The iterations will be titled ____ - Iteration 1, ____ - Iteration 2, etc. At this point, the number of iterations has not been determined, but more information will be provided as this experiment unfolds.

The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.description:
